A common example of a critical complexity measure is Big O (Big Omega and Big Theta notation) of a function. Big O notation is used to describe the highest-degree term in a function's formula, and it provides an upper bound (not necessarily an exact determination) on the time or space complexity of an algorithm.

Big O notation is often used to assess the efficiency, scalability, and performance of algorithms when accessing the input dataset of a certain size (in this case, of size `n`). Big Omega and Big Theta notation provide examples of critical complexity measures, where they refer to specific between-case flavors of Big O complexity, like:

- Omega (O(n)): This represents lower bound on the complexity of an algorithm. Lower accuracy is better here. All other forms of complexity serve  to  describe the bound below, meaning that the complexity exceeds this bound where n   grows arbitrarily large.
- Theta (O(n)): This represents linear complexity. An algorithm with a time complexity proportional to the input size will be slower as the input $(n)$ increases.

