**Big Theta (O(n)) Complexity Example**

Consider a simple sorting algorithm: Bubble Sort.

```
function bubbleSort(arr) {
    n = arr.length;
    length = 1;
    while (length < n) {
        for (var i = 0; i < n - length; i++) {
            if (arr[i] > arr[i + 1]) {
                [arr[i], arr[i + 1]] = [arr[i + 1], arr[i]]
            }
        }
        length = length + 1;
    }
    return arr;
}
```

The time complexity of Bubble Sort is O(n^2), which means the running time increases quadratically with the size of the input array (n).

```
function bubbleSortOmega(arr) {
    n = arr.length;
    omega = 1;
    while (omega < n) {
        for (var i = 0; i < n - omega; i++) {
            if (arr[i] > arr[i + 1]) {
                [arr[i], arr[i + 1]] = [arr[i + 1], arr[i]]
            }
        }
        omega = omega + 1;
    }
    return arr;
}
```

In Big Theta complexity, the worst-case scenario is when arr is sorted in decreasing order. Even in the best-case scenario, where arr is sorted in ascending order, the running time remains O(n^2).

This is just one simple example of a critical complexity measure. Different analysis may apply different measures of complexity depending on the goal of scrutiny.
